title: Time series
body:
Hi,

This patch add support for downloading data from Quandl as timeSeries class. Obviously the conversion is rather trivial, but I think it would be useful nevertheless. I tend to use Rmetrics packages quite often and those prefer timeSeries data.

There was some problem with the unit tests, in the search test the returned list has zero length. The for loop would traverse the indices from 1 to 0 which causes an indexing error. I added a check to avoid that case so the test cases should all pass now.

Ditching XML for JSON for imporved speed and 50% less query to Quandl servers
body:
What I did not like in the prior implementation is that the `Quandl` function was querying the servers twice:
- once to check if the data exists and to identify frequency,
- then really fetched data.

I wanted to merge these two process, but `XML` parsing seems to be really slow compared to `JSON`, which latter tends to have smaller size too. So suggesting to drop `XML` for the really fast parser of `RSJONIO`.

I have made a quick comparison of the two methods:

``` rout
> library(microbenchmark)
> Quandl.XML  <- function() x <- Quandl("NSE/OIL")
> Quandl.JSON <- function() x <- Quandl2("NSE/OIL")
> microbenchmark(Quandl.XML(), Quandl.JSON(), times = 10)
Unit: milliseconds
          expr      min        lq    median        uq      max neval
  Quandl.XML() 993.8316 1053.9598 1094.4323 1110.6291 1192.171    10
 Quandl.JSON() 848.3522  895.3143  908.8844  945.8231 1024.257    10
```

![compare](https://f.cloud.github.com/assets/495736/221428/7d0da5b6-859b-11e2-8d6f-6f72c4a08b16.png)

So we can see some speed improvement, and also less load on your servers for sure.

---

Although I have tested the rewritten parts, it's without any warranty of course :)

Although there are some differences in the results of the functions:

``` rout
> identical(Quandl("NSE/OIL"), Quandl2("NSE/OIL"))
 [1] FALSE
```

That's just thanks to the column names, as `read.csv` forces safe names:

``` rout
> Quandl.XML()
'data.frame':   857 obs. of  8 variables:
 $ Date                : Date, format: "2009-09-30" "2009-10-01" ...
 $ Open                : num  1096 1102 1152 1150 1154 ...
 $ High                : num  1157 1174 1166 1157 1161 ...
 $ Low                 : num  1090 1102 1137 1132 1140 ...
 $ Last                : num  1135 1167 1143 1143 1141 ...
 $ Close               : num  1141 1166 1141 1145 1142 ...
 $ Total.Trade.Quantity: num  19748012 3074254 919832 627957 698216 ...
 $ Turnover..Lacs.     : num  223877 35464 10581 7186 8033 ...
> Quandl.JSON()
'data.frame':   857 obs. of  8 variables:
 $ Date                : Date, format: "2009-09-30" "2009-10-01" ...
 $ Open                : num  1096 1102 1152 1150 1154 ...
 $ High                : num  1157 1174 1166 1157 1161 ...
 $ Low                 : num  1090 1102 1137 1132 1140 ...
 $ Last                : num  1135 1167 1143 1143 1141 ...
 $ Close               : num  1141 1166 1141 1145 1142 ...
 $ Total Trade Quantity: num  19748012 3074254 919832 627957 698216 ...
 $ Turnover (Lacs)     : num  223877 35464 10581 7186 8033 ...
```

This can be also done with the current method too, although I prefer to use human readable variable names :)

And of course feel free to ignore this pull request if you insist on using `XML`.

title: Small tweaks and cleanup, roxygenize and import instead of depends
body:
As discussed with @RaymondMcT in e-mail, I have tweaked the package a bit. Please review and feel free to merge or ignore my commits here. I tried to make short and separate commits so that the review could be any easy process, but in short, I've done the following stuff:
- cleaning-up unnecessary elements (e.g. the `.DS_store` files might go to `.gitignore`, not sure about your added but not used `Rdata` and some lines of code like the `library` calls and `new.env`)
- roxygenized the docs so that you would not need to hand-edit the `Rd` files. See the references in the commit message.
- I did not want to touch your coding sytle, but after much refactoring I decided to make it closer to what Hadley suggested in his nice wiki (pls see my commit msg for references)
- and removed the packages from the `Depends` field of your `DESCRIPTION` file and rather `Importing` package function now to keep the clutter of function names at a minimal level in the `.GlobalEnv`.

As far I as tested, the package works fine after my modifications, but please be sure to review and test it. And sorry for much modifications, I hope you do not mind. Maybe a version bump should have also been attached, but I did not want to tweak your `DESCRIPTION` file any further.
